            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>What is the Child-Pugh score?</h2>
              <p>
                The Child–Pugh score (also called Child–Turcotte–Pugh, CTP) is a
                clinical tool used to estimate the severity and prognosis of
                chronic liver disease, mainly cirrhosis. It combines laboratory
                values and clinical findings to classify patients into:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Class A (5–6 points):</strong> well-compensated
                  disease
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Class B (7–9 points):</strong> significant functional
                  compromise
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Class C (10–15 points):</strong> decompensated
                  cirrhosis, poor prognosis
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The score is widely used to estimate mortality risk, guide
                timing of transplant referral, assess suitability for surgery or
                TIPS, and adjust dosing of drugs in hepatic impairment.
              </p>

              <h2>Child-Pugh score components and points</h2>
              <p>
                The Child-Pugh score uses five parameters, each scored from 1 to
                3 points.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">1. Serum bilirubin</h3>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <strong>1 point:</strong> &lt; 2 mg/dL (&lt; 34 µmol/L)
                  </li>
                  <li><strong>2 points:</strong> 2–3 mg/dL (34–50 µmol/L)</li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>3 points:</strong> &gt; 3 mg/dL (&gt; 50 µmol/L)
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <h3 class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-2">2. Serum albumin</h3>
                <ul>
                  <li><strong>1 point:</strong> &gt; 3.5 g/dL</li>
                  <li><strong>2 points:</strong> 2.8–3.5 g/dL</li>
                  <li><strong>3 points:</strong> &lt; 2.8 g/dL</li>
                </ul>
                <h3 class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-2">
                  3. Coagulation (INR or PT prolongation)
                </h3>
                <p class="mb-1"><strong>Using INR:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                  <li><strong>1 point:</strong> &lt; 1.7</li>
                  <li><strong>2 points:</strong> 1.7–2.3</li>
                  <li><strong>3 points:</strong> &gt; 2.3</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="mt-2 mb-1">
                  <strong
                    >Using PT prolongation (seconds above control):</strong
                  >
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li><strong>1 point:</strong> &lt; 4 seconds</li>
                  <li><strong>2 points:</strong> 4–6 seconds</li>
                  <li><strong>3 points:</strong> &gt; 6 seconds</li>
                </ul>
                <h3 class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-2">4. Ascites</h3>
                <ul>
                  <li><strong>1 point:</strong> None</li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>2 points:</strong> Mild, controlled with diuretics
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>3 points:</strong> Moderate–severe, refractory to
                    diuretics
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <h3 class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-2">
                  5. Hepatic encephalopathy
                </h3>
                <ul>
                  <li><strong>1 point:</strong> None</li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>2 points:</strong> Grade I–II or controlled with
                    treatment
                  </li>
                  <li><strong>3 points:</strong> Grade III–IV or refractory</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h2>How the Child-Pugh score is calculated</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Assign 1–3 points to each of the five parameters according to
                  the table above.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Add the points to obtain a total score between 5 and 15.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Determine the Child-Pugh class:
                  <ul>
                    <li><strong>Class A:</strong> 5–6 points</li>
                    <li><strong>Class B:</strong> 7–9 points</li>
                    <li><strong>Class C:</strong> 10–15 points</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Typical prognosis by Child-Pugh class</h2>
              <p>
                Survival estimates vary between studies and depend on etiology,
                comorbidities, and treatment. Commonly cited approximate 1-year
                survival rates are:
              </p>
              <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-200 mt-2">
                <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                  <tr>
                    <th class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 text-left">
                      Class
                    </th>
                    <th class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 text-left">
                      Score
                    </th>
                    <th class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 text-left">
                      Approx. 1-year survival
                    </th>
                    <th class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 text-left">
                      Description
                    </th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 font-semibold">
                      A
                    </td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">5–6</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">~95%</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Well-compensated cirrhosis
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 font-semibold">
                      B
                    </td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">7–9</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">~75–80%</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Significant functional compromise
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 font-semibold">
                      C
                    </td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">10–15</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">~45–55%</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Decompensated cirrhosis, poor prognosis
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-1">
                Values are approximate and for educational purposes only. Always
                refer to up-to-date clinical guidelines and literature.
              </p>

              <h2>Clinical uses and limitations</h2>
              <h3>Common uses</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Baseline risk stratification in cirrhosis</li>
                <li>Estimating perioperative risk for non-hepatic surgery</li>
                <li>
                  Assessing suitability and timing for TIPS or liver
                  transplantation
                </li>
                <li>
                  Guiding dose adjustments for drugs metabolized by the liver
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Limitations</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Subjective components (ascites, encephalopathy) can vary
                  between observers.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not include creatinine or sodium, so it may underestimate
                  risk in renal dysfunction.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Not validated for all liver diseases (e.g., acute liver
                  failure).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Should be used together with other scores (e.g., MELD,
                  MELD-Na) and full clinical assessment.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
              <h3>Is Child-Pugh or MELD better?</h3>
              <p>
                They answer slightly different questions.
                <strong>MELD/MELD-Na</strong> is more objective and is the
                standard for liver transplant allocation.
                <strong>Child-Pugh</strong> remains widely used for general
                prognosis, surgical risk, and drug dosing recommendations in
                hepatic impairment.
              </p>

              <h3>Which value should I use for PT?</h3>
              <p>
                If you use PT, enter the
                <strong>prolongation above control</strong> (e.g., patient PT 18
                s, control 12 s → prolongation 6 s). If INR is available, it is
                usually preferred because it is standardized.
              </p>

              <h3>Can patients use this calculator on their own?</h3>
              <p>
                This tool is designed for healthcare professionals. Patients may
                use it for education, but should not make any treatment
                decisions based on the result. Always discuss your score and
                prognosis with your hepatologist or treating physician.
              </p>

              <h2>Disclaimer</h2>
              <p class="text-xs text-gray-600">
                This Child-Pugh score calculator is provided for educational and
                decision-support purposes only. It does not constitute medical
                advice and must not be used as a substitute for professional
                clinical judgment. Always confirm calculations and management
